  "context": "Mall shops and chain stores in Hong Kong have fixed prices, fitting rooms, and card payment. Sizes are labelled S/M/L or by chest and waist. No bargaining here; that belongs to the street markets.",
  "cultural_note": "The concept of 開市 (hoi1 si5, \"opening the market\") shapes the start of trading at Hong Kong's street stalls and wet markets: the first sale of the day is considered auspicious, bringing luck for all business that follows. Vendors are more willing to negotiate in the first hour of trading, whenever that falls, midday at Mong Kok's Ladies' Market, late afternoon at Temple Street. Arriving as the stalls open and making a polite offer is considered entirely proper.",
